name: Ambystoma tigrinum
verbatimLocality: 4446–4998 Collegeview Rd E, Rochester, Minnesota, US
occurrenceRemarks: On our way home from skating we took some back roads to my parents. We started seeing (and hearing) frogs jumping in the road and banging into the car and then we saw something with a longer body and tail and to our surprise it was a juvenile tiger salamander, must have just recently metamorphosized and was migrating from a pond to the woods to go underground. We ran home and picked up Jenna and headed back out. All of a sudden the tiger salamanders were everywhere. We were stopping every few minutes. We started collecting then to see how many we could catch but we ran out of space in the container we brought so we started just moving them off the road so as not to get hit. Altogether we must have seen over 50 plus a bunch of DOR and a few frogs and toads. We brought about 20 home to show the rest of family and take pics of including putting then in my moms fountain. Then we went and brought them all back and distributed them where we found them. Did not take pics of each one or GPS points so I'm just posting this one observation but it counts for 50+ tigers. Seeing this tiger salamander migration was amazing and probably one of my best herp outings in my life!

name: Ambystoma tigrinum
verbatimLocality: 5455 Eisenhower Ln SE, Rochester, Minnesota, US
occurrenceRemarks: Even though I have found tiger salamanders before when I was younger and living in MN, I'm gonna call this a lifer since it has been a long time. This was found under my parents patio the last night we were in town for a visit. The kids and I were doing one last hunt for toads and as I approached the patio I saw a head of something sticking out and then duck back under. I bent down and looked under with flashlight and there was this guy looking back at me. I could not get him to come out so I found a cricket and attached to a piece of wire and fished him out! It must have been the impending rain conditions that caused him to come out because I never saw any signs of him all the previous nights we looked around the house.
